    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The dissonance of a minor second can be attributed to the frequency ratio between the two notes. In this case, a minor second involves a frequency ratio of 9:8, which is slightly detuned from the ideal 10:9 ratio of a perfect fifth. This detuning creates a sense of tension and instability in the ear, as the brain struggles to reconcile the slightly mismatched frequencies. This phenomenon is known as \"just intonation\" and is thought to be an evolutionary adaptation to help us detect potential threats or warning signals, such as the call of a predator. In the case of a minor second, the slight detuning can be perceived as a warning signal, alerting the listener to the presence of something out of tune or discordant.",
